  "prompt": "Why do capacitors store energy?",
  "response": "Capacitors store energy due to the separation of electric charges between two conductive plates separated by an insulating material called a dielectric. Here's a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. Basic Mechanism:\n- When a voltage is applied across a capacitor's plates, positive and negative charges accumulate on opposite sides\n- These separated charges create an electric field within the dielectric material\n- The electric field represents stored potential energy\n\n2. Charge Separation:\n- Electrons are pushed away from one plate to the other\n- This creates a charge difference between the plates\n- Energy is required to create this charge separation\n\n3. Electrostatic Potential:\n- The electric field between plates creates an electrostatic potential\n- The energy stored is proportional to the charge and voltage\n- The formula is: Energy = \u00bd \u00d7 Capacitance \u00d7 (Voltage)\u00b2\n\n4. Dielectric Properties:\n- The insulating material between plates helps maintain charge separation\n- Different dielectrics can enhance energy storage capacity\n- Prevents direct charge transfer between plates\n\n5. Energy Release:\n- When connected to a circuit, charges can flow between plates\n- This releases the stored electrical energy\n- Can happen quickly, making capacitors useful in many electronic applications\n\nThe ability to store and release energy quickly makes capacitors crucial in electronic circuits.",
